"Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang"

Zhang Shizhi, the Tingwei, was a native of Duyang, styled Jì. He lived with his elder brother Zhong. Appointed as a Cavalry Lang due to his family's wealth, he served Emperor Xiaowen for ten years without promotion or recognition. Shizhi said, "Long service has diminished Zhong's estate; I cannot succeed." He wished to resign and return home. The Zhonglangjiang Yuan Ang, knowing his worth and regretting his departure, requested that Shizhi be transferred to fill the position of Yezhe. After Shizhi had finished his audience, he spoke on matters of immediate benefit. Emperor Xiaowen said, "Keep it low; do not speak too highly, but propose what can be implemented now." Thus, Shizhi spoke at length on events between the Qin and Han dynasties, explaining why Qin fell and why Han rose. Emperor Xiaowen praised him and appointed Shizhi as Yezhe Puye.

Shizhi accompanied the Emperor, ascending the Tiger Enclosure. The Emperor asked the Shanglin Wei about the registers of various beasts; after more than ten questions, the Wei looked left and right, unable to answer any. The Tiger Enclosure Shefu, standing nearby, answered the Emperor's questions about the beast registers in great detail, wishing to display his ability to respond instantly and endlessly. Emperor Xiaowen said, "Should not officials be like this? The Wei is useless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the Shefu as Shanglin Ling. Shizhi stepped forward and said, "Your Majesty, how do you regard Jiahou Zhou Bo?" The Emperor replied, "A virtuous elder." He asked again, "And what of Dongyanghou Zhang Xiang?" The Emperor again said, "A virtuous elder." Shizhi said, "Jiahou and Dongyanghou are called virtuous elders; these two men could hardly speak when discussing affairs. How could they be compared to this Shefu, who is talkative, sharp-tongued, and quick-witted! Moreover, Qin relied on clerks skilled in writing; officials competed to excel in speed and harsh scrutiny. Yet the result was merely empty formalities, lacking true compassion. Therefore, their faults went unheard, and the dynasty declined until the Second Emperor, when the realm collapsed like an earthen mound. Now, Your Majesty promotes this Shefu solely for his eloquence. I fear the whole world will follow suit, competing in empty talk without substance. Furthermore, the people's imitation of their superiors is as swift as the shadow follows the body or the echo follows the sound; every action must be carefully considered." Emperor Xiaowen said, "Good." He then stopped and did not appoint the Shefu.

The Emperor entered his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride with him, and proceeded slowly, asking Shizhi about the faults of Qin. Shizhi answered fully and truthfully. Upon reaching the palace, the Emperor appointed Shizhi as Gongche Ling.

Shortly after, the Crown Prince and the Prince of Liang entered the court together in one carriage without dismounting at the Sima Gate. Shizhi pursued and stopped them, forbidding entry to the palace gates. He then impeached them for failing to dismount at the public gate, an act of disrespect, and submitted the report. Empress Dowager Bo heard of this. Emperor Xiaowen removed his cap and apologized, saying, "I have not taught my sons carefully." Empress Dowager Bo then sent an envoy with an imperial decree to pardon the Crown Prince and the Prince of Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. Emperor Xiaowen thus regarded Shizhi as extraordinary and appointed him Zhongdafu.

Soon after, he became Zhonglangjiang. Accompanying the Emperor to Baling, they sat facing north near a latrine. At that time, Lady Shen accompanied them. The Emperor pointed out the Xinfeng Road to Lady Shen, saying, "This is the road to Handan." He had Lady Shen play the se, while he leaned on the se and sang, his mood sorrowful and melancholy. Turning to his ministers, he said, "Alas! If we use stones from Beishan for the outer coffin, fill the gaps with hemp and cotton, and seal them with lacquer, could it possibly be moved?" Those around him all said, "Good." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is anything desirable inside, even if sealed with the Southern Mountain, there will still be a crack. If there is nothing desirable inside, even without a stone coffin, what need for sorrow?" Emperor Xiaowen praised him. Later, Shizhi was appointed Tingwei.

Shortly after, the Emperor went out through the Middle Wei Bridge. A man emerged from under the bridge, startling the imperial horses. The Emperor ordered cavalry to capture him and handed him over to the Tingwei. Shizhi investigated and questioned him. The man said, "I am a county resident. Hearing the imperial procession, I hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, I came out. Seeing the imperial carriages and cavalry, I simply ran." The Tingwei sentenced him: one person violated the imperial procession ban; the penalty is a fine. Emperor Xiaowen was angry and said, "This man personally startled my horse. Fortunately, my horse was gentle. Had it been another horse, would it not have injured me? Yet the Tingwei sentences him only to a fine!" Shizhi replied, "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. Now, if the law is thus and we increase the penalty, the law will lose credibility among the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered immediate execution, it would have been done. Now that the case is with the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the balance of the world. If it tilts once, all application of law throughout the realm will become arbitrary. Where will the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long time, the Emperor said, "The Tingwei's judgment is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seat in the High Temple. Captured, the thief was handed to the Tingwei for trial. Shizhi, according to the law, reported that stealing items used by the imperial ancestors in the temple warrants execution by beheading in the market. Emperor Xiaowen was furious and said, "This man is utterly without principle, stealing vessels from the late Emperor's temple. I handed him to the Tingwei intending to have his whole clan executed, yet you report according to the law. This is not how I intend to honor the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his cap, bowed his head to the ground, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Moreover, crimes of equal severity differ based on whether they are committed in defiance or obedience. Now, if stealing temple vessels leads to clan execution, and if one in ten thousand were to take a handful of earth from Changling, how would Your Majesty increase the punishment?" After a long time, Emperor Xiaowen discussed this with the Empress Dowager and finally approved the Tingwei's judgment. At that time, the Zhongwei, Tiaohou Zhou Yafu, and the Liang Prime Minister, Shanduhou Wang Tiankai, seeing that Shizhi upheld justice impartially, became his close friends. Zhang Tingwei was thus praised throughout the world.

Later, Emperor Xiaowen died and Emperor Jingdi ascended the throne. Shizhi, fearing, claimed illness and wished to resign, dreading severe punishment. Yet he also wished to appear and apologize, not knowing how it would go. Following Wang Sheng's advice, he finally appeared and apologized; Emperor Jingdi did not hold it against him.

Wang Sheng was a recluse skilled in Huang-Lao teachings. Once summoned to stand in the court while the Three Dukes and Nine Ministers were all assembled, the elderly Wang Sheng said, "My sock has come undone," and turned to Zhang Tingwei, saying, "Tie my sock for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone asked Wang Sheng, "Why did you humiliate Zhang Tingwei in court, making him kneel to tie your sock?" Wang Sheng replied, "I am old and lowly; I judge that I can never benefit Zhang Tingwei. Zhang Tingwei is now a famous minister of the world. I therefore deliberately humiliated him, making him kneel to tie my sock, to enhance his reputation." When the nobles heard this, they esteemed Wang Sheng and held Zhang Tingwei in even higher regard.

Zhang Tingwei served Emperor Jingdi for over a year, then became the Prime Minister of Huainan, still regarded as having past faults. After some time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, styled Changgong, who reached the rank of Dafu but was dismissed. Because he could not accommodate himself to the times, he never held office again.

Feng Tang's great-grandfather was from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When Han rose, they moved to Anling. Tang was renowned for filial piety and served as Zhonglang Shuzhang under Emperor Xiaowen. When the Emperor passed by in his carriage, he asked Tang, "Old man, how did you become a Lang? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Xiaowen said, "When I resided in Dai, my food supervisor Gao Qu often spoke to me of the virtue of Zhao General Li Qi, who fought under Julu. Now, whenever I eat, my thoughts are never far from Julu. Do you know of him?" Tang replied, "He is not as good as Lian Po and Li Mu as generals." The Emperor asked, "Why?" Tang said, "When my great-grandfather was in Zhao, he served as a commander and was friendly with Li Mu. My father formerly served as Dai Prime Minister and was friendly with Zhao General Li Qi, knowing his character." After hearing of Lian Po and Li Mu, the Emperor was greatly pleased and struck his thigh, saying, "Alas! If only I could have Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals in my time; would I then worry about the Xiongnu?" Tang said, "My Lord! Even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not employ them." The Emperor became angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and reproached him, saying, "Why did you humiliate me in public? Could you not have done so in private?" Tang apologized, saying, "I am a rustic man and do not know taboos."

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently invaded Chaona in great force, killing the Beidi Commandant Ang. The Emperor, concerned about the barbarian raids, finally asked Tang again, "How do you know I cannot employ Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied, "I have heard that ancient kings, when sending generals, would kneel and push the chariot wheel, saying, 'Within the threshold, I, the ruler, decide; beyond the threshold, the general decides.' Military merits, ranks, and rewards were all decided in the field and reported upon return. This is not empty talk. My great-grandfather said that when Li Mu served as Zhao general on the border, the taxes from the military market were used entirely to feast the soldiers; rewards were decided in the field without interference from the court. Entrusted with responsibility and held accountable for success, Li Mu was thus able to fully employ his wisdom and ability. He dispatched one thousand three hundred chariots, thirteen thousand cavalry, and one hundred thousand elite warriors. Thus, he drove the Chanyu north, defeated the Donghu, destroyed the Danlin, suppressed the powerful Qin in the west, and supported Han and Wei in the south. At that time, Zhao nearly achieved hegemony. Later, when Zhao King Qian ascended the throne—his mother being a singer—King Qian, influenced by the slander of Guo Kai, executed Li Mu and replaced him with Yan Ju. Consequently, the army was defeated, the soldiers fled, and Zhao was captured and destroyed by Qin. Now, I have secretly heard that Wei Shang, as Governor of Yunzhong, used all taxes from the military market to feast his soldiers, spent his own money, and every five days slaughtered an ox to feast guests, military officers, and attendants. Thus, the Xiongnu stayed far away and did not approach the Yunzhong passes. When the enemy once entered, Shang led his chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many. The soldiers are all sons of common families, recruited from the fields; how could they know the military registers and tally slips? Fighting bravely all day, beheading and capturing enemies, they submit their merits to the headquarters. If a single word does not match, clerks punish them according to law. Rewards are not given, but officials strictly enforce the law. I am foolish, but I believe Your Majesty's laws are too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, Yunzhong Governor Wei Shang was punished for a discrepancy of six heads in his reported kills; Your Majesty handed him to the officials, stripped him of his rank, and sentenced him to penal labor. From this, it follows that even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not employ them. I am truly foolish, have offended taboos, and deserve death. Death, death!" Emperor Xiaowen was pleased. That day, he ordered Feng Tang to hold the imperial tally, pardon Wei Shang, restore him as Governor of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as Cheqi Duwei, in charge of the Zhongwei and the chariot and infantry forces of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jingdi ascended the throne and appointed Tang as Prime Minister of Chu, later dismissing him. When Emperor Wudi ascended, seeking virtuous and talented men, Feng Tang was recommended. Tang was then over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official, so his son Feng Sui was appointed as a Lang. Sui, styled Wangsun, was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji's words on virtuous elders show adherence to law without pandering; Feng Gong's discourse on generals is profound! Profound indeed! As the saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The praises of these two gentlemen are worthy of being inscribed in the halls of state. The Book of Documents says, "Not partial, not factional, the Way of the King is broad; not factional, not partial, the Way of the King is clear." Zhang Ji and Feng Gong come close to this. [end of text]


